Phil (Ham-Call KO6BB)
3.0 out of 5 stars Suitable for some general purpose stuff, but. . .
Reviewed in the United States on December 22, 2015
Verified Purchase
I've been 'doing' radio and electronics both professionally and as a hobby for over 60 years (I nearly always open a review with this comment as a point of reference). I've used a LOT of banana plugs over the years and have a firm grasp of what I like and don't like about them. I just wish I could find the 'classic' banana plugs like I used to buy years ago. Anyway, here's my likes and dislikes about this particular one.
LIKES:
1. Fairly easy to put on a cable, IF the cable is of a large enough gauge for the screw to "bite down on". It helps to tin the wire with your soldering iron first too.
2. I like the plastic insulated covers. I bought some "$$$" gold Banana Plugs, but they're not very safe to use on test equipment etc where you have high Voltage on the leads. For connecting power supplies etc these are safer (see cons about current capacity though).
3. Price is very reasonable, especially if you're buying enough 'stuff' from Amazon to get the free shipping.

Dislikes (Cons):
1. I have a number of items with "short" panel mount banana jacks on them, as well as the "wrist-strap" grounding posts on my workbench. These plugs WILL NOT fit that type of Banana Jack, they're loose and fall out (the fat grippy part of the plug is too far back).
2. I mentioned power supply connections. I'm not at all sure that these would be a safe or reliable connection for anything drawing much current (say maybe over an Amp). I say that because I plugged a pair of test leads with these plugs into one of my (lab) DVMs, put the DVM on a low Ohms range and measured the resistance through them. As I wiggled the plug the resistance changed from a fraction of an Ohm to several Ohms (probably the "part that turns" to the center shaft resistance). I suspect that in power connections (like powering even a modestly small Ham Radio from a power supply) the Voltage drop (and maybe generated heat) would be unacceptable.

Upshot. Probably very suitable for something like a speaker connections etc, but don't rely on them in the home lab or Ham Shack. . .
